Important Concept : 
When we write:ch++;
It increases the character by 1 in ASCII value.
Example:
'A' → 'B'
'B' → 'C'
'Z' → next ASCII character, Because internally characters are stored as numbers.
For example:
'A' = 65
'B' = 66
'C' = 67
So ch++ simply increases that number by 1.

Code : 

public class CharacterPattern {
  public static void main(String args[]) {

    int n = 4;
    char ch = 'A';

    for (int line = 1; line <= n; line++) {
      for (int letter = 1; letter <= line; letter++) {
        System.out.print(ch);
        ch++;
      }
      System.out.println();
    }
  }
}


